{
  "text": "Generally, most DSMLs implicitly enforce that both ends of a relationship are bounded to classifiers to represent which classifier drives a behavior and which classifier reacts to the action. In some cases, one end of the relation can be open. A DSML for representing chemical structure [CITATION_1] can be a good example for this case because some chemical structures have lone pairs of electrons, which are not involved in chemical bond formation, as well as bonding pairs.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "9120606"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "9120606": {
      "title": "SYBYL Line Notation (SLN): A Versatile Language for Chemical Structure Representation",
      "abstract": "SYBYL Line Notation (SLN) is an ASCII language used to represent chemical structures, including common organic molecules, macromolecules, polymers, and combinatorial libraries. SLN is also used to express substructural (2D) queries and includes a complete facility for Markush representation. This concise language is ideal for database storage of chemical entities as well as for network communication of structures and queries."
    }
  }
}